Int+J+Mol+Sci%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Int+J+Mol+Sci%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2025 Jan 21;26(3):875.\n\ndoi: 10.3390/ijms26030875.\n\n# The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans\n\n[Matteo Amadei](/?term=Amadei+M&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\") ,¬†[Fabio Polticelli](/?term=Polticelli+F&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [2](#full-view-affiliation-2 \"Department of Sciences, University Roma Tre, 00146 Rome, Italy.\") ,¬†[Giovanni Musci](/?term=Musci+G&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [3](#full-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of Biosciences and Territory, University of Molise, 86090 Pesche, Italy.\") ,¬†[Maria Carmela Bonaccorsi di Patti](/?term=Bonaccorsi+di+Patti+MC&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\")\n\nAffiliations Expand\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\n-   2 Department of Sciences, University Roma Tre, 00146 Rome, Italy.\n-   3 Department of Biosciences and Territory, University of Molise, 86090 Pesche, Italy.\n\n-   PMID: **39940646**\n-   PMCID: [PMC11817551](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11817551/)\n-   DOI: [10.3390/ijms26030875](https://doi.org/10.3390/ijms26030875)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nReview\n\n# The Ferroxidase-Permease System for Transport of Iron Across Membranes: From Yeast to Humans\n\nMatteo Amadei¬†et al. Int J Mol Sci. 2025.\n\nShow details\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat Abstract PubMed PMID\n\nInt J Mol Sci\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Int+J+Mol+Sci%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Int+J+Mol+Sci%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2025 Jan 21;26(3):875.\n\ndoi: 10.3390/ijms26030875.\n\n### Authors\n\n[Matteo Amadei](/?term=Amadei+M&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\") ,¬†[Fabio Polticelli](/?term=Polticelli+F&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Department of Sciences, University Roma Tre, 00146 Rome, Italy.\") ,¬†[Giovanni Musci](/?term=Musci+G&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [3](#short-view-affiliation-3 \"Department of Biosciences and Territory, University of Molise, 86090 Pesche, Italy.\") ,¬†[Maria Carmela Bonaccorsi di Patti](/?term=Bonaccorsi+di+Patti+MC&cauthor_id=39940646)¬† [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\")\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Department of Biochemical Sciences 'A. Rossi Fanelli', Sapienza University of Rome, 00185 Rome, Italy.\n-   2 Department of Sciences, University Roma Tre, 00146 Rome, Italy.\n-   3 Department of Biosciences and Territory, University of Molise, 86090 Pesche, Italy.\n\n-   PMID: **39940646**\n-   PMCID: [PMC11817551](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11817551/)\n-   DOI: [10.3390/ijms26030875](https://doi.org/10.3390/ijms26030875)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nFull text links Cite\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat AbstractPubMedPMID\n\n## Abstract\n\nTransport of iron across the cell membrane is a tightly controlled process carried out by specific proteins in all living cells. In yeast and in mammals, a system formed by an enzyme with ferroxidase activity coupled to a membrane transporter supports iron uptake or iron efflux, respectively. Ferroxidase belongs to the family of blue multicopper oxidases, enzymes able to couple the one-electron oxidation of substrate(s) to full reduction of molecular oxygen to water. On the other hand, the permeases are widely different and are specific to Fe3+ and Fe2+ in yeast and multicellular organisms, respectively. This review will describe the yeast and human ferroxidase-permease systems, highlighting similarities and differences in structure, function and regulation of the respective protein components.\n\n**Keywords:** Fet3; Ftr1; ceruloplasmin; copper; ferroportin; ferroxidase; hephaestin; iron; multicopper oxidase; yeast.\n\n[PubMed Disclaimer](/disclaimer/)\n\n## Conflict of interest statement\n\nThe authors declare no conflict of interest.\n\n## Figures\n\n [![Figure 1](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/a63d88defc49/ijms-26-00875-g001.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/72df9b960693/ijms-26-00875-g001.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 1\n\n**\n\nThe yeast and human ferroxidase‚Äďpermease‚Ä¶\n\n**\n\nFigure 1\n\n**\n\nThe yeast and human ferroxidase‚Äďpermease system. Fpn: ferroportin; Cp: ceruloplasmin; Heph: hephaestin.\n\n**Figure 1**\n\nThe yeast and human ferroxidase‚Äďpermease system. Fpn: ferroportin; Cp: ceruloplasmin; Heph: hephaestin.\n\n [![Figure 2](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/c91eaa5cae96/ijms-26-00875-g002.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/f0f3544c8dfd/ijms-26-00875-g002.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 2\n\n**\n\nFe binding site in Fet3‚Ä¶\n\n**\n\nFigure 2\n\n**\n\nFe binding site in Fet3 (PDB ID 1ZPU). The 3D structure of the‚Ä¶\n\n**Figure 2**\n\nFe binding site in Fet3 (PDB ID 1ZPU). The 3D structure of the protein is shown (**a**), together with a close-up view of the Fe-binding site (**b**). The T1 Cu atom is colored blue, the TNC is in cyan. Residues E185, D283 and D409 are colored in red, green and magenta, respectively. T1 Cu ligands and the His-Cys-His T1 Cu-TNC branched pathway are highlighted.\n\n [![Figure 3](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/424bc11f5ca5/ijms-26-00875-g003.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/d4ed6cb1a18e/ijms-26-00875-g003.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 3\n\n**\n\nFe binding sites in domains‚Ä¶\n\n**\n\nFigure 3\n\n**\n\nFe binding sites in domains 4 and 6 of Cp (PDB ID 2J5W).‚Ä¶\n\n**Figure 3**\n\nFe binding sites in domains 4 and 6 of Cp (PDB ID 2J5W). The 3D structure of the protein is shown (**a**), together with a close-up view of the metal-binding sites (**b**). The T1 Cu atoms are colored blue, the TNC is cyan with dioxygen in orange. The metal atom in the Fe-binding site in domain 6 is in red, side chains involved in Fe binding are highlighted, together with the His-Cys-His T1 Cu-TNC branched pathway.\n\n [![Figure 4](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/e7860d5a06ba/ijms-26-00875-g004.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/47f55e9cb943/ijms-26-00875-g004.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 4\n\n**\n\nAlphaFold model of *S. cerevisiae* ‚Ä¶\n\n**\n\nFigure 4\n\n**\n\nAlphaFold model of *S. cerevisiae* Ftr1 (Uniprot ID: P40088) with acidic residues of‚Ä¶\n\n**Figure 4**\n\nAlphaFold model of *S. cerevisiae* Ftr1 (Uniprot ID: P40088) with acidic residues of REXLE, E89 and DASE motifs evidenced in red, magenta and cyan respectively (**a**). Negatively charged surface patch on the extracellular side of Ftr1 (**b**).\n\n [![Figure 5](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/0ab8123c6d1b/ijms-26-00875-g005.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/01ee/11817551/f9954c08e0d0/ijms-26-00875-g005.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 5\n\n**\n\nSchematic representation of the three-dimensional‚Ä¶\n\n**\n\nFigure 5\n\n**\n\nSchematic representation of the three-dimensional structure of human Fpn in complex with Co ‚Ä¶\n\n**Figure 5**\n\nSchematic representation of the three-dimensional structure of human Fpn in complex with Co2+ (PDB ID 8Dl8). The first and second repeat of the N-domain are in orange and light blue, respectively. The corresponding repeats of the C-domain are in red and blue. The large intracellular region connecting the two domains is in gray. Metal binding residues are shown in stick representation, and the cobalt ions are shown as pink spheres.\n\n[See this image and copyright information in PMC](#)\n\n## References\n\n1.  1.  Winterbourn C.C. Toxicity of Iron and Hydrogen Peroxide: The Fenton Reaction. Toxicol. Lett. 1995;82‚Äď83:969‚Äď974. doi: 10.1016/0378-4274(95)03532-X. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4274\\(95\\)03532-x) - [PubMed](/8597169/)\n2.  1.  Harrison P.M., Arosio P. The Ferritins: Molecular Properties, Iron Storage Function and Cellular Regulation. Biochim. Biophys. Acta (BBA) Bioenerg. 1996;1275:161‚Äď203. doi: 10.1016/0005-2728(96)00022-9. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/0005-2728\\(96\\)00022-9) - [PubMed](/8695634/)\n3.  1.  Honarmand Ebrahimi K., Bill E., Hagedoorn P.-L., Hagen W.R. The Catalytic Center of Ferritin Regulates Iron Storage via Fe(II)-Fe(III) Displacement. Nat. Chem. Biol. 2012;8:941‚Äď948. doi: 10.1038/nchembio.1071. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1038/nchembio.1071) - [PubMed](/23001032/)\n4.  1.  Honarmand Ebrahimi K., Hagedoorn P.-L., Hagen W.R. Unity in the Biochemistry of the Iron-Storage Proteins Ferritin and Bacterioferritin. Chem. Rev. 2015;115:295‚Äď326. doi: 10.1021/cr5004908. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1021/cr5004908) - [PubMed](/25418839/)\n5.  1.  Bernacchioni C., Pozzi C., Di Pisa F., Mangani S., Turano P. Ferroxidase Activity in Eukaryotic Ferritin Is Controlled by Accessory-Iron-Binding Sites in the Catalytic Cavity. Chem. Eur. J. 2016;22:16213‚Äď16219. doi: 10.1002/chem.201602842. - [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1002/chem.201602842) - [PubMed](/27650996/)\n\nShow all 146 references\n\n## Publication types\n\n-   Review\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Review%22%5Bpt%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Review)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n\n## MeSH terms\n\n-   Animals\n    \n    Actions\n    \